<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-204-123 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 432 969</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  March 8 1991* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>NY State Police arrest alleged hacker &quot;Scorpion&quot;. (Paul Stira)</TITLE><AUTHOR>McMullen, Barbara E.; McMullen, John F.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer hackersGovernment AgencyLegal IssuesCourt Cases.andO;Person:    Stira, Paul (Cases).andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>****NY STATE POLICE ARREST ALLEGED HACKER &quot;SCORPION&quot; 03/08/91 NEW YORK, NEWYORK, U.S.A., 1991 MAR 8 (NB) -- The US Secret Service has announced, inconjunction with the New York State Police, that it has arrested Paul Stira,20, a student known by the hacker name of &quot;Scorpion.&quot; Police say Stira brokeinto computers owned by BellSouth and WNET, among others.andM;Stira is charged with device fraud, a violation of Federal Code 1049, whichdeals with unauthorized access to computer systems as well as falsificationof telephone credit card calling numbers.andM;Stira has been the subject of an on-going investigation that became publicknowledge with the execution of the search warrant and seizure of computerequipment in January, 1990.andM;Secret Service Agent James Lewer told Newsbytes that Stira and anotherwell-known New York &quot;hacker,&quot; Acid Phreak, had received letters from theUnited States Attorney's Office in Brooklyn, a few weeks ago, saying thatindictments were pending.andP;  They were offered the opportunity to have theirattorney contact the US Attorney and discuss the possible indictments.andP;  AcidPhreak chose to contact the US Attorney, according to Lewer, and indicatedthat he would cooperate with the on-going investigation.andM;Stira did not contact the US Attorney and therefore has been arrested andcharged with the alleged crimes.andP;  Lewer also said that Stira, upon hisarrest, had expressed interest in cooperation.andM;New York State Police Senior Investigator Donald Delaney, who alsoparticipated in the arrest, told Newsbytes, &quot;Stira was the last of four whosehomes were searched in January, 1990.andP;  Stira indicated that, from hiscontacts at the monthly &quot;2600&quot; hacker meetings, computer crime is way down.andO;Perhaps the investigatory efforts of the various police agencies have led tothis decrease.&quot;andM;The charges against Stira carry a maximum penalty of up to 10 years inprison.andM;(Barbara E. McMullen andamp; John F. McMullen/19910308)</TEXT></DOC>